We quote from the book “Madeira” written by André Simon, founder of the Wine & Food Society and one of the world's leading gastronomic authorities. “In January 1933, Dr. Michael Grabham, ‘the grand old man’ of Madeira, celebrated his ninety-third birthday, which was the occasion on which I tasted for the first time an authentic 1792 Madeira, perfect as regards colour, bouquet and flavor.” On that occasion the good Dr. Grabham stated “This wine was made in 1792, a very good year indeed—it was given to me in 1873. It has been with me during the past 60 years. There is very little left, and it is better today than it ever was.

And it is of historical interest to note that the “London Daily $265 00 Telegraph” of October 8th, 1841 refers to the vintage 1792 as The Case

having been purchased by Napoleon in 1815 to comfort him in his exile when he called at Madeira on his way further south to St. Helena.

The entire contents of the cask were bottled, interrupting a 165 year slumber, to commem- orate the visit, last year, of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II to Portugal. Our tasting notes read “amazing vigor, penetrating bouquet, great depth of flavor, relatively dry—rivals fine old Cognac in scope and interest.” | |

Because precious few bottles exist in the world, we suggest prompt acquisition—even a single bottle will add its touch of lustre to the most distinguished cellar, historic interest to the holiday dinner party, and heartwarming joy as a unique Christmas gift to an appre- ciative friend.
